Reading the assigned chapters from the book, I was kind of surprised. I think the idea of HyperCities is super cool, the idea isn't super complicated on paper. But it's something that I'm surprised I hadn't seen before. I really liked the three kinds of temporality described, as it uses concepts I know inherently but haven't thought of explicitly. Concerning mapping protests, I think there's something special there to be spoken for. It helps to bring the people together and add cohesiveness to the cause, again why I'm surprised I havent seen something like this before. A question I have for the authors is, "How would you change aspects of the project to account for the ambiguity/ uncertainty or bias in working with social media data.
